Function to get the number of images in the directory

In [277]:
def numberoffiles(path):
    if not os.path.exists(path):
        return 0
    return sum([len(files) for r, d, files in os.walk(path)])

Next, we load the model from Imagenet, that has been pretrained to work with the image datasets. The model consists of 308 layers in total, with repetitions of Convolutions, Poolingn and Normalization layers.

Loading pretrained Inception model from imagenet along with the weights:

In [293]:
#Load the inception model and load with its pre trained weight
V3_base_model = InceptionV3(weights='imagenet', include_top=False)     
print('Inception v3 base model without the last layer loaded')

Inception v3 base model without the last layer loaded

Using the GoogleLeNet architecture, we make use of the InceptionV3 pretrained model for our image classification exercsie. The main idea behind the inception models is to make use of parallel training of model for image features, so that it can save computational resources as well as feed of the performance and the training from the previous layer. It adds a set of 1x1, 3x3, 5x5 inception, pooling and reduce layers to offer the same deeper model performance in lower computational space.

Adding final layers to the pretrained model to customize for the classification probelem of Cats and Dogs

In [298]:
x = V3_base_model.output 
x_pool = GlobalAveragePooling2D()(x)
x_dense = Dense(Number_FC_Neurons,activation='relu')(x_pool)
final_pred = Dense(num_classes,activation='softmax')(x_dense)
model = Model(inputs=V3_base_model.input,outputs=final_pred)

Adding model refinements with loss functions and optimizer

In [299]:
#Fine tune model by retraining the few end layers of the inception model

layers=154    
for layer in model.layers[:layers]:
    layer.trainable =False
for layer in model.layers[layers:]:
    layer.trainable=True

    sgd = SGD(lr = 0.01, decay = 1e-6, momentum = 0.9, nesterov = True)
model.compile(optimizer=sgd,loss='binary_crossentropy',metrics=['accuracy'])

Nesterov Accelerated Gradient helps to arrive at the local optimum (minima) much faster than the normal gradient boosting, by estimating the direction in which it should approch in the next iteration. We make use of NAG to speed up the loss minimization while still following the gradient descent methodology.

Since our problem involves only two classes, we can assume the binary cross entropy function to give us accurate loss value and we do not have to look for categorical cross entropy. The same is seen in the performance of model.

Kaggle Submissions

On uploading to the Kaggle Competitions page, the output model achieves a score of 2.87.

To improve this score, we increase the number of epochs in our model to 5 and train it on the Kaggle Platform directly to utilize the GPU strength

We also use more layers in the model (from the Inception pretrained space) and thereby, more parameters to help with the accuracy.

In the final model, the number of neurons were changed from 1024 to 256, and the image resolution from 320x320 to 256x256.

The final score received from our best model submission to Kaggle gives out a score of 0.0510
